"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 7–8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1chronicles-7-8.py

Ch 7: Tribal genealogies of Issachar, Benjamin (first register), Naphtali, Manasseh,
      Ephraim (including mourning, Sheerah's city-building, the line to Joshua), Asher
Ch 8: Benjamin's full genealogy; Saul's line through to his descendants including Meribbaal

Key Christological decisions:
- Ch 7 Naphtali (v13): shadow — Galilee of the Gentiles where Christ began ministry (Isa 9:1-2 / Matt 4:15)
- Ch 7 Ephraim→Joshua (v27): type — Joshua as the explicit type of Christ's rest-giving in Heb 4:8
- v24 Sheerah built Beth-horon: shadow — city/inheritance building → the eternal inheritance Christ secures (Heb 11:10)
- Ch 8 v33 Saul's genealogy: shadow — Saul's failed kingship points to David → Christ as the true king
- Ch 8 v34 Meribbaal: type — lame man at the king's table = the sinner welcomed to the messianic feast (Luke 14:21)
- Asher's closing v40 and Anna the prophetess (Luke 2:36-38): allusion — a daughter of Asher recognized the infant Christ
- Most genealogical-list verses: brief 'theme' or 'revelation of God' entries — covenant people preserved through
  history, anticipating all-Israel's eschatological ingathering in Christ
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The theme of election runs through the entire chapter: tribal rolls that appear to be administrative records are the register of a covenant people through whom God was advancing his redemptive purposes toward Christ. Issachar&rsquo;s four sons each becoming a lineage mirrors the covenant&rsquo;s expansion from Abraham&rsquo;s one son to the vast assembly promised in Gen 15:5. The counting of God&rsquo;s people is itself a sign of covenant faithfulness (Num 1:2: YHWH commands a census as enumeration of his redeemed), culminating in Rev 7:9: &lsquo;a great multitude that no one could number, from every nation.&rsquo;</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Issacharite heads of ancestral houses and mighty warriors display the theme that the covenant people are also a fighting people — God&rsquo;s redemptive history advances through real historical agency: armies, families, migrations. The NT presents Christ as the one who fulfills the warrior motif: the Divine Warrior of Rev 19:11-16 who finally defeats the enemies of God&rsquo;s people not through conventional warfare but through the cross and resurrection.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Five great-grandsons of Issachar each leading armies demonstrates the generational amplification of covenant blessing: one man becomes four sons, who become lineages of tens of thousands. This multiplication pattern runs from the Abrahamic promise (&lsquo;as the stars of heaven&rsquo;) through the genealogies of Chronicles to its eschatological fulfillment in Rev 7:9: &lsquo;a great multitude that no one could number, from every nation.&rsquo;</p>",
    "4": "<p>Thirty-six thousand troops from Issachar&rsquo;s line &lsquo;ready for war&rsquo; — the military readiness of God&rsquo;s people is a recurring OT theme. The shadow of this military calling points forward to the spiritual warfare of Eph 6:10-18: the people of Christ fight not against flesh and blood but against spiritual powers, equipped with the full armor of God rather than shields and spears.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Eighty-seven thousand mighty warriors across all Issachar&rsquo;s families. The Issachar blessing in Gen 49:14-15 describes the tribe as accepting the yoke of service; Deut 33:18-19 promises Issachar&rsquo;s participation in the abundance of the covenant. The NT continues the twelve-tribe structure in Rev 7:7, including 12,000 from Issachar in the sealed multitude of the new covenant community — the genealogical roll becomes the eschatological register.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy appears twice in Chronicles (here and ch. 8), reflecting multiple source documents and the Chronicler&rsquo;s interest in this tribe. Benjamin&rsquo;s theological significance in the messianic narrative is immense: from this tribe came Saul the first king and Paul the apostle — the paradox that the youngest, smallest son-tribe (Deut 33:12: &lsquo;beloved, in whom YHWH shelters&rsquo;) produces both the failed king and the apostle whose proclamation built the church reflects the divine pattern of choosing the unlikely for pivotal purposes.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Belaite clan producing twenty-two thousand warriors (v9). The theme of the firstborn runs throughout Scripture as a Christological marker: Christ is the &lsquo;firstborn of all creation&rsquo; and &lsquo;firstborn from the dead&rsquo; (Col 1:15,18), the one to whom all firstborn honors ultimately point. The fecundity of Benjamin&rsquo;s firstborn clan demonstrates the covenant blessing operating at the sub-tribal level.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Becher&rsquo;s nine sons — among them Anathoth. Anathoth is the priestly city of Jeremiah&rsquo;s birth (Jer 1:1), the prophet whose suffering most closely anticipates the suffering Servant and whose new-covenant prophecy (Jer 31:31-34) is the NT&rsquo;s most-cited OT text for the establishment Christ makes. A geographical name within Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy carries the weight of the greatest prophetic announcement of the covenant Christ establishes.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The enrollment formula — &lsquo;genealogical enrollment according to their generations, as heads of ancestral houses&rsquo; — reflects the Levitical principle that covenant membership is registered, known, and preserved. In the NT, this register motif is fulfilled in the &lsquo;Lamb&rsquo;s book of life&rsquo; (Rev 21:27; Phil 4:3): the definitive roll of those who belong to the covenant community secured by Christ&rsquo;s blood.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Jediael-Bilhan line producing seventeen thousand warriors (v11). Benjamin&rsquo;s martial excellence is the shadow of the one true Warrior who emerges from the covenant people. Paul boasts of his Benjaminite identity even while rejecting it as a basis for confidence (Phil 3:5-7) — the tribe&rsquo;s strength is no longer the ground of standing before God, because Christ has become our wisdom, righteousness, sanctification, and redemption (1 Cor 1:30).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Seventeen thousand two hundred warriors from Jediael&rsquo;s line &lsquo;ready to go to war.&rsquo; The readiness theme in these military rosters anticipates the eschatological readiness of Christ&rsquo;s people: &lsquo;be ready, for the Son of Man is coming at an hour you do not expect&rsquo; (Matt 24:44). The muster at Hebron (1 Chr 12) where all Israel crowned David is the immediate fulfillment; the parousia is the ultimate one.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Shuppim and Huppim, sons of Ir; Hushim, son of Aher — closing the first Benjamin section briefly. God&rsquo;s purposes do not require equal treatment of every genealogical line; the covenant advances through chosen streams while maintaining the integrity of all twelve tribes. The Chronicler&rsquo;s theological honesty in preserving minor sub-lines reflects the conviction that no covenant family is lost from YHWH&rsquo;s register.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: Naphtali&rsquo;s four sons, descended from Bilhah Rachel&rsquo;s maidservant — the concubine-son tribes are included in the covenant register without distinction. Isaiah&rsquo;s prophecy identifies Naphtali&rsquo;s territory (&lsquo;Galilee of the nations&rsquo;) as the land where the Messiah&rsquo;s light would first dawn: &lsquo;the people who walked in darkness have seen a great light&rsquo; (Isa 9:1-2). Matthew 4:13-16 explicitly fulfills this prophecy: Jesus moved to Capernaum, in Naphtali&rsquo;s territory, to begin his public ministry. The brief Naphtali genealogy is the hidden register of the tribe that would first see the dawn of redemption.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Manasseh&rsquo;s line includes an Aramean concubine who bore Machir and Ashriel — the presence of a non-Israelite woman in the tribal genealogy is one of the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent inclusions of Gentile lineages within the covenant people (cf. Ruth the Moabitess in the Davidic line, Rahab, Uriah the Hittite). These Gentile threads woven into the genealogical fabric from the beginning are shadows of the Gentile inclusion that Christ formally inaugurates: &lsquo;he has broken down the dividing wall of hostility&rsquo; (Eph 2:14), creating one new humanity from Jew and Gentile alike.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Machir took wives for Huppim and Shuppim; Zelophehad is named. The daughters of Zelophehad successfully petitioned Moses for an inheritance when no male heir existed (Num 27:1-11) — a narrative about women receiving the covenant inheritance. This anticipates the NT reversal in which all believers, regardless of status, receive the inheritance of the Spirit (Gal 3:28-29): &lsquo;There is neither Jew nor Greek, slave nor free, male nor female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus.&rsquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>Machir&rsquo;s wife Maachah bore Peresh and Sheresh — &lsquo;root&rsquo; (<em>šōreš</em>) is the term Isaiah uses for the Messiah: &lsquo;There shall come forth a shoot from the stump of Jesse, and a branch from his roots shall bear fruit&rsquo; (Isa 11:1); &lsquo;the root of Jesse&rsquo; is quoted in Rom 15:12 as fulfilled in Christ. The name Sheresh within Manasseh&rsquo;s genealogy does not predict this — but the root-tree imagery that pervades the messianic prophecies begins in the naming culture of Israel&rsquo;s tribes.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ulam son of Bedan within Gilead&rsquo;s descendants. The covenant claim to the contested Gileadite territory (Transjordan, fought over by Ammon, Moab, Aram, and Israel) reflects YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty over territory that appeared politically insecure — a theme the NT fulfills in Christ&rsquo;s claim that all authority in heaven and on earth belongs to him (Matt 28:18), the ground of the universal commission to disciple all nations.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hammoleketh (&lsquo;the queen&rsquo;) bore Ishhod, Abiezer, and Mahalah. Abiezer is the clan of Gideon (Judg 6:11,34) — the weak judge from a weak clan chosen to deliver Israel from Midian, whose story anticipates the pattern of divine strength perfected in human weakness (2 Cor 12:9). The connection of Gideon&rsquo;s clan to this woman named &lsquo;the queen&rsquo; grounds the judge&rsquo;s calling in the genealogical purposes of God, where the pattern of power-through-weakness is embedded even in the naming.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The sons of Shemida — four more Manassehite clan heads, including Shechem. Shechem is the city where the kingdom divided under Rehoboam (1 Kgs 12:1) and where Jacob buried the foreign gods (Gen 35:4) — a site of both failure and covenant renewal. Jesus&rsquo; conversation with the Samaritan woman at &lsquo;Sychar, near the field that Jacob gave to his son Joseph&rsquo; (John 4:5 — Sychar being ancient Shechem) deliberately reclaims this contested location for the new covenant people.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Ephraim genealogy opens with a chain: Shuthelah, Bered, Tahath, Eladah, Tahath, Zabad, Shuthelah — Ephraim was the dominant northern tribe, the tribe of Joshua, the tribe that gave its name to the northern kingdom. The story of its near-destruction at Gath (vv21-22) and recovery through Joshua (v27) is a microcosm of the covenant people&rsquo;s pattern: defeat, mourning, resurrection, and inheritance — the pattern Christ fulfills structurally in his death and resurrection.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Ezer and Elead were killed by the men of Gath when they raided the Gaathites&rsquo; livestock. The killing of covenant-people sons by Gentile enemies follows the pattern of Herod killing the Bethlehem infants (Matt 2:16-18): the enemy strikes at the covenant line to destroy the Redeemer. In both cases, the effort fails — the covenant line continues through Beriah (v23) just as Christ survived Herod. The pattern of enemy-assault followed by covenant-continuation is the grammar of redemptive history.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Their father Ephraim mourned many days, and his brothers came to comfort him — the grief of a father over slain sons. The mourning-comforting pattern runs from Job&rsquo;s comforters through Rachel weeping (Jer 31:15, quoted in Matt 2:18 for Herod&rsquo;s massacre) to Christ weeping at Lazarus&rsquo;s tomb (John 11:35). God does not bypass grief but moves through it. Christ is the one who &lsquo;bore our griefs and carried our sorrows&rsquo; (Isa 53:4), transforming every Ephraim-mourning into resurrection joy.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Ephraim went in to his wife; she conceived and bore Beriah (<em>bərîʿāh</em>), named &lsquo;because disaster (<em>bĕrāʿāh</em>) had come upon his house.&rsquo; The naming of a child in grief — the covenant continuing through catastrophe — is the pattern of Rachel naming Ben-oni (son of my sorrow) as she died, and of Eli&rsquo;s daughter-in-law naming Ichabod (&lsquo;the glory has departed&rsquo;) after the ark&rsquo;s capture. The covenant line is never more fragile than when a father names his son after disaster — and never more visibly sustained by YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness, which is precisely what these names confess.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A shadow: Sheerah, Ephraim&rsquo;s daughter, built Lower and Upper Beth-horon and Uzzen-sheerah. Beth-horon was the site of Joshua&rsquo;s great victory (Josh 10:10-11: YHWH hurled hailstones as the Amorites fled down the Beth-horon descent). The city-building motif points toward the heavenly city (Heb 11:10,16: Abraham was looking for &lsquo;the city that has foundations, whose designer and builder is God&rsquo;) — the inheritance Christ secures for his people. Sheerah builds with material stones; Christ builds the eternal city not made with hands (2 Cor 5:1; Rev 21:2-3).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Rephah and Resheph, Telah, Tahan — continuing Ephraim&rsquo;s line after the Gath disaster. The continuation of the genealogy after vv21-23&rsquo;s catastrophe is itself a theological statement: grief does not terminate the covenant line. The same pattern repeats after Israel&rsquo;s exile — the genealogies of Ezra-Nehemiah demonstrate that YHWH preserved a remnant through Babylon. The final expression of this preserving faithfulness is the resurrection: not even death can terminate the covenant that God establishes in Christ.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Ladan, Ammihud, Elishama — names that appear in Numbers as Ephraimite chieftains (Elishama son of Ammihud commanded Ephraim&rsquo;s division in the wilderness march, Num 10:22). The genealogy threads the wilderness registers into the later tribal lineage, confirming the continuous covenant identity from Egypt through Canaan. Christ is &lsquo;the same yesterday, today, and forever&rsquo; (Heb 13:8) — the covenant&rsquo;s continuity across centuries of tribal registers is a shadow of that constancy.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A type: &lsquo;his son Non, his son Joshua.&rsquo; Joshua (<em>Yᵉhôšuaʿ</em>, &lsquo;YHWH saves&rsquo;) is the Hebrew form of the name Jesus (<em>Iēsous</em>). The book of Hebrews explicitly treats Joshua as a type who fails to give the ultimate rest: &lsquo;For if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken of another day later on&rsquo; (Heb 4:8). The type is structural: Joshua leads Israel across the Jordan into the Promised Land, defeating enemies and distributing the inheritance — exactly what Jesus does spiritually, leading his people through death into the resurrection-life inheritance. Joshua&rsquo;s name as the culminating name in Ephraim&rsquo;s genealogy — after eleven ancestors, after the Gath disaster and Beriah&rsquo;s grief-birth — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s quiet placement of the greatest type of Christ within the tribal roll.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Ephraim&rsquo;s settlements — Bethel, Naaran, Gezer, Shechem — are among the most theologically dense locations in the OT. Bethel is where Jacob saw the ladder to heaven (Gen 28:10-22: &lsquo;how awesome is this place! This is none other than the house of God&rsquo;) — and where Jesus promises the disciples they will see heaven opened and angels ascending and descending on the Son of Man (John 1:51), claiming Jacob&rsquo;s vision for himself. The tribal map of Ephraim is inscribed with redemptive-historical memory that Christ inhabits and fulfills.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Along the borders of Manasseh: Beth-shean, Taanach, Megiddo, Dor. Megiddo&rsquo;s name resonates in Revelation as &lsquo;Har-Magedon&rsquo; (Rev 16:16) — the symbolic gathering point for the final conflict of the age. The geographical detail of v29 maps the terrain where Israel&rsquo;s history was contested; the same terrain where the eschatological drama of Christ&rsquo;s ultimate victory is symbolically located. The sons of Joseph held these territories as their inheritance; Christ&rsquo;s final victory is what their settlement foreshadows.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Asher&rsquo;s four sons and one daughter Serah. A tradition in later Jewish sources credits Serah with extraordinary longevity and wisdom — confirming Moses&rsquo; identity and later recognizing the ark&rsquo;s location. Whether or not these traditions are historical, Serah&rsquo;s repeated appearance across the genealogical records (Gen 46:17; Num 26:46; here) suggests she was a memorable figure whose wisdom-memory was preserved across generations, a shadow of the wisdom that was &lsquo;with God at the beginning&rsquo; (Prov 8:22-31) and that &lsquo;became flesh&rsquo; in Christ (John 1:14).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Beriah and Malchiel, father of Birzaith — Asher&rsquo;s line in the coastal northwest. The covenant people spread across all twelve tribal territories points toward the eschatological ingathering: Isaiah&rsquo;s promise that the exiles would be gathered &lsquo;from the four corners of the earth&rsquo; (Isa 11:12) encompasses all twelve tribes, including Asher in the far north. Christ as the Good Shepherd who gathers his flock from all directions (John 10:16; 11:52) fulfills the ingathering promised to each scattered tribe.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Heber fathered Japhlet, Shomer, Hotham, and their sister Shua — again a daughter named in a patrilineal genealogy. The inclusion of women&rsquo;s names (Sheerah in v24, Serah in v30, Hammoleketh in v18, Shua here) across these chapters is a persistent feature that anticipates the NT pattern where women are specifically included in the genealogy of Christ (Matt 1:3-6: Tamar, Rahab, Ruth, Bathsheba) and among his most faithful witnesses (Luke 24:22-24).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The sons of Japhlet — three Asherite sub-clan names. Asher failed to drive out the Canaanites and Phoenicians from their coastal territory (Judg 1:31-32), living among them instead. This incomplete possession of the inheritance reflects the OT land possession&rsquo;s structural incompleteness — a theme Hebrews interprets typologically: the rest given in Canaan was not the ultimate rest, pointing to the &lsquo;Sabbath rest for the people of God&rsquo; that remains (Heb 4:9), the rest Christ provides.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The sons of Shemer — Ahi, Rohgah, Jehubbah, and Aram. The name Aram within Asher&rsquo;s lineage (a possible Aramean connection within an Israelite tribe) is another example of non-Israelite threads woven into the covenant fabric — the Gentile inclusion that Christ formally enacts (Eph 2:11-22) was prepared for by the mixed-ethnic reality of every tribal genealogy in the OT.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The sons of Helem — Zophah, Imna, Shelesh, and Amal. The Chronicler&rsquo;s genealogical thoroughness reflects the conviction that no covenant family is lost from the record. This register-keeping is a shadow of YHWH&rsquo;s own omniscient record: &lsquo;Are not five sparrows sold for two pennies? And not one of them is forgotten before God. Why, even the hairs of your head are all numbered&rsquo; (Luke 12:6-7). The God who keeps genealogical registers keeps every name of every person who belongs to him.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Six sons of Zophah — Suah, Harnepher, Shual, Beri, Imrah, continuing in v37. The genealogical rolls were identity documents for the post-exilic community; these names confirmed that Asherite families retained their covenant standing and tribal membership after returning from Babylon. The same principle applies to the NT: in Christ, every believer&rsquo;s name is written in heaven (Luke 10:20), secured not by tribal lineage but by the once-for-all sacrifice that established the new covenant.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Bezer, Hod, Shamma, Shilshah, Ithran, and Beera — completing Zophah&rsquo;s sons. The persistence of non-Israelite names within Israelite genealogies (Ithran echoes the Edomite Ithran of Gen 36:26) reflects the ancient world&rsquo;s mixed-ethnic character of every tribal system. The canonical significance: the covenant people were never ethnically pure, and the church&rsquo;s inclusion of Gentiles in Christ is continuous with rather than a departure from this founding pattern in Israel&rsquo;s own genealogies.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The sons of Jether — Jephunneh, Pispa, and Ara. Jephunneh is Caleb&rsquo;s father&rsquo;s name (Num 13:6) — Caleb the Kenizzite incorporated into Judah, who wholly followed YHWH (Num 14:24) and received his inheritance even in old age (Josh 14:10-12). The appearance of this name in Asher&rsquo;s lineage draws together the trans-tribal network that knit Israel into one covenant people. Christ is the head whose body&rsquo;s members share one name: &lsquo;every family in heaven and on earth is named&rsquo; from the Father (Eph 3:14-15).</p>",
    "39": "<p>The sons of Ulla — Arah, Hanniel, and Rizia. Hanniel means &lsquo;God is gracious&rsquo; (same root as John/Johanan/Hannah). The grace-name within Asher&rsquo;s closing genealogy is fitting: God&rsquo;s gracious preservation of twelve tribes through exodus, conquest, monarchy, exile, and return is the story these genealogies collectively tell. The grace that the name Hanniel encodes is ultimately expressed in the incarnate Son: &lsquo;For the law was given through Moses; grace and truth came through Jesus Christ&rsquo; (John 1:17).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The closing summary of Asher: &lsquo;chosen men, mighty warriors, outstanding leaders.&rsquo; The language of &lsquo;chosen&rsquo; (<em>bᵉrûrîm</em>) echoes YHWH&rsquo;s choosing of Israel as his treasured people (Deut 7:6). The NT transfers this chosen-people identity to the church: &lsquo;But you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation&rsquo; (1 Pet 2:9). That Anna the prophetess from the tribe of Asher (Luke 2:36-38) recognized the infant Christ as &lsquo;the redemption of Jerusalem&rsquo; is the chapter&rsquo;s quiet Christological fulfillment: from this warrior lineage came one whose eyes of faith recognized the dawn of the promised redemption in a child at the temple.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy begins again — the second, fuller register of this tribe in Chronicles. Benjamin (<em>ben yāmîn</em>, &lsquo;son of the right hand&rsquo;) holds a paradoxical position in messianic history: from this tribe came Saul the failed king and Paul the apostle. The tribe of the right hand produces both the king whose kingdom fell and the apostle whose proclamation built the church. The right-hand position (&lsquo;son of the right&rsquo;) anticipates the NT&rsquo;s royal image: Christ seated at the right hand of God (Ps 110:1; Matt 26:64; Heb 1:3), the ultimate &lsquo;son of the right hand.&rsquo;</p>",
    "2": "<p>Nohah the fourth and Rapha the fifth — completing Benjamin&rsquo;s five sons. The name Rapha (<em>rāpāʾ</em>, &lsquo;the healer&rsquo;) carried healing resonance in Israel&rsquo;s naming culture. Christ as the great healer who came from the covenant people (Matt 4:23: &lsquo;healing every disease and every affliction&rsquo;) is the ultimate fulfillment of every healing-name embedded in Israel&rsquo;s genealogies. YHWH-Rapha (&lsquo;the LORD who heals you,&rsquo; Exod 15:26) is the divine name that these genealogical names echo.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The sons of Bela, beginning with Addar and Gera. Gera is a recurring Benjaminite clan name: Ehud the left-handed judge was son of Gera (Judg 3:15), and Shimei who cursed David was son of Gera (2 Sam 16:5). The same clan name produces a deliverer and a curser — the Benjaminite capacity for both faithfulness and rebellion is encapsulated in the onomastic record. Christ is the one who transforms curser into worshipper: he prayed for those who cursed him (Luke 23:34), fulfilling the covenant&rsquo;s deepest intention.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Abishua, Naaman, and Ahoah. The name Naaman (<em>naʿᵃmān</em>, &lsquo;pleasant&rsquo;) anticipates the Aramean general healed of leprosy by Elisha (2 Kgs 5:1-19), who confessed &lsquo;there is no God in all the earth but in Israel.&rsquo; Jesus himself cites Naaman as an example of God&rsquo;s grace extending beyond Israel: &lsquo;there were many lepers in Israel in the time of the prophet Elisha, and none of them was cleansed, but only Naaman the Syrian&rsquo; (Luke 4:27). The name appears in Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy as a quiet anticipation of the Gentile who would bear it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Gera, Shephuphan, and Huram — completing Bela&rsquo;s sons. The persistence of clan names across centuries (Shephuphan/Huppim appear in Gen 46:21 and Num 26:39) reflects the covenant community&rsquo;s commitment to preserving its lineage — the same commitment that makes the NT genealogies of Christ (Matt 1; Luke 3) meaningful: Christ&rsquo;s ancestry was verifiable through exactly this kind of preserved genealogical record. The incarnation is grounded in history, not myth.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The sons of Ehud, heads of ancestral houses at Geba, carried into exile to Manahath. Ehud the Benjaminite judge (Judg 3:15-30) was the left-handed deliverer who killed Eglon. The exile and continuation pattern is the Chronicler&rsquo;s constant theme: God&rsquo;s purposes advance through displacement — the same pattern the NT applies to Christ&rsquo;s death-and-resurrection, the ultimate exile-and-return through which the new creation is inaugurated.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Naaman, Ahijah, and Gera — three sub-clan leaders within Ehud&rsquo;s line, displaced from Geba to Manahath. The forced relocation whose reason is not given reflects YHWH&rsquo;s superintendence of historical events that appear unexplained. The God who preserved covenant people through such dislocations is the same God who &lsquo;works all things according to the counsel of his will&rsquo; (Eph 1:11), including the apparently purposeless dislocations of his people&rsquo;s lives.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Shaharaim fathered children in Moab after divorcing his wives — a Benjaminite establishing a family in Moab. The Moab connection runs through David&rsquo;s ancestry (Ruth the Moabitess) and surfaces again within Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy. The presence of Israelite men in Moab (Elimelech in Ruth 1:1-2; Shaharaim here) reflects the geographic porosity between Transjordan and the west-bank tribes. Christ&rsquo;s genealogy through Ruth demonstrates that the covenant&rsquo;s reach extends into Moab — and through Christ to all nations.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shaharaim&rsquo;s seven sons by Hodesh — Jobab, Zibia, Mesha, Malcam, Jeuz, Sachia, and Mirmah. The name Malcam (&lsquo;their king&rsquo; or &lsquo;Milcom,&rsquo; the Ammonite god) within a Benjaminite genealogy reflects the religious syncretism surrounding the covenant community. The covenant people were always embedded in a polytheistic environment; Christ&rsquo;s redemption includes reclaiming people from the orbit of competing loyalties — transforming those whose names invoke false kings into those who confess the one true King.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jeuz, Sachia, and Mirmah — Shaharaim&rsquo;s Moabite-born sons as &lsquo;heads of ancestral houses.&rsquo; The Chronicler does not exclude these Moabite-born Benjaminites from Israel&rsquo;s covenant register. This reflects the principle that covenant membership is determined by descent from the covenant patriarch and participation in the community&rsquo;s identity — a principle fulfilled in Christ, in whom &lsquo;there is neither Jew nor Greek&rsquo; (Gal 3:28) yet all are heirs of Abraham&rsquo;s promise (Gal 3:29).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Abitub and Elpaal, sons by Hushim — the children of the discarded wife registered in Israel&rsquo;s covenant roll. The inclusion of a divorced woman&rsquo;s sons within the genealogical record reflects YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness to those marginalized by human failure. Christ&rsquo;s ministry especially extended to those excluded — the divorced, the socially discarded — precisely because the covenant God had always tracked those whom human society wrote off.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elpaal&rsquo;s sons — including Shemed who built Ono and Lod. Lod (Lydda) was where Peter healed the paralytic Aeneas: &lsquo;Aeneas, Jesus Christ heals you; rise and make your bed&rsquo; (Acts 9:34). The city that Shemed (a Benjaminite) founded in the settlement period became the location of one of the apostle Paul&rsquo;s fellow-Benjaminite Peter&rsquo;s healing miracles in the name of Christ. The geographical inheritance first claimed by Benjamin&rsquo;s sons becomes the setting for the new covenant community&rsquo;s apostolic activity.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Beriah and Shema, heads of houses at Aijalon who drove out the inhabitants of Gath. Aijalon was Joshua&rsquo;s battle site (Josh 10:12: &lsquo;Sun, stand still at Gibeon, and moon, in the Valley of Aijalon&rsquo;) where YHWH fought with miraculous hailstones. The Benjaminites who drove out Gath&rsquo;s inhabitants from Aijalon reverse the earlier defeat where Gath&rsquo;s men killed Ephraimite sons (7:21). The pattern of defeat followed by victory in the same geographic corridor reflects the covenant narrative&rsquo;s trajectory: the enemies who struck first are ultimately overcome — as death is overcome in Christ&rsquo;s resurrection.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ahio, Shashak, and Jeremoth. The name Jeremoth recurs across tribes in Chronicles (a Levitical musician in 1 Chr 25:22; men who married foreign wives in Ezra 10). The spread of names across tribes reflects the shared naming culture of Israel that made the twelve tribes one people. Christ&rsquo;s body is similarly one people with shared identity across every background: &lsquo;one body and one Spirit&rsquo; (Eph 4:4) whose members share one name.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Zebadiah, Arad, and Eder — sons of Beriah. The name Arad recalls the Canaanite city Israel first defeated in the Negev by vow (Num 21:1-3: Israel vowed to devote the cities to destruction and YHWH gave them the victory). The naming of an Israelite child Arad suggests the assimilation of conquered place-names into the covenant community&rsquo;s naming culture — the people carrying their history of YHWH&rsquo;s victories in their very names.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Michael, Ishpah, and Joha — sons of Beriah. Michael (<em>mîḵāʾēl</em>, &lsquo;Who is like God?&rsquo;) is the name of the archangel-warrior who fights for Israel against spiritual powers (Dan 10:13,21; Rev 12:7). The name within Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy is a reminder that the human tribe of warriors is sustained by Michael&rsquo;s cosmic warfare — the spiritual dimension of Israel&rsquo;s military history that the NT exposes: &lsquo;we do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against... the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly places&rsquo; (Eph 6:12), defeated by Christ&rsquo;s cross (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Zebadiah, Meshullam, Hizki, and Heber — sons of Elpaal. Meshullam (<em>mᵉšullām</em>, &lsquo;at peace&rsquo; — from <em>šālôm</em>) was among the most common names in the post-exilic period, reflecting the Hebrew longing for <em>šālôm</em>: the wholeness and peace the prophets promised as the Messiah&rsquo;s gift (Isa 9:6: &lsquo;Prince of Peace&rsquo;; 52:7: &lsquo;How beautiful are the feet of him who brings good news, who publishes peace&rsquo;). Every Meshullam in the genealogical record carries the unspoken petition for the peace Christ finally gives (John 14:27: &lsquo;Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you&rsquo;).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Ishmerai, Izliah, and Jobab — sons of Elpaal. Jobab is the name of an early Edomite king (Gen 36:33-34) and possibly identifies with Job in some traditions (LXX Job appendix). If the connection to Job is ancient, then a Benjaminite bearing this name carries the memory of the Gentile who declared &lsquo;I know that my Redeemer lives, and at the last he will stand upon the earth&rsquo; (Job 19:25) — the resurrection hope grasped by one outside Israel before Israel had articulated it clearly.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jakim, Zichri, and Zabdi — sons of Shimei. Zichri (<em>ziḵrî</em>, &lsquo;my remembrance&rsquo;) marks YHWH&rsquo;s remembrance (<em>zeḵer</em>) of his covenant — the basis for every redemptive act from Noah (Gen 8:1: &lsquo;God remembered Noah&rsquo;) through the Exodus (Exod 2:24: &lsquo;God remembered his covenant&rsquo;) to the incarnation (Luke 1:54-55: &lsquo;He has helped his servant Israel, in remembrance of his mercy&rsquo;). The name Zichri embedded in Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy is a covenant-memory marker pointing toward the God who never forgets his people.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Elienai, Zillethai, and Eliel — sons of Shimei. The El-names cluster (&lsquo;God is my help,&rsquo; &lsquo;shade of God,&rsquo; &lsquo;God is exalted&rsquo;) in one verse reflect the depth of Israel&rsquo;s naming culture: every name is a statement about YHWH. The accumulation of divine-attribute names is the onomastic equivalent of the divine name&rsquo;s declaration in Exod 34:6-7. The God known by his attributes — mercy, grace, faithfulness, justice — is the same God who revealed all his attributes in their fullness in Christ (Col 2:9: &lsquo;in him the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily&rsquo;).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Adaiah, Beraiah, and Shimrath — sons of Shimei. Adaiah (<em>ʿăḏāyāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH has adorned&rsquo;) appears in Nehemiah as the name of a returned exile who settled in Jerusalem (Neh 11:5,12) — the post-exilic restoration community included descendants of exactly these Benjaminite clans. The Chronicler&rsquo;s genealogical project is identity-documentation for that community: you belong to this covenant people, your exile is over. The NT applies the same logic to the church: &lsquo;you are no longer strangers and aliens, but fellow citizens with the saints and members of the household of God&rsquo; (Eph 2:19).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Ishpan, Eber, and Eliel — sons of Shashak. Eber (<em>ʿēḇer</em>, &lsquo;beyond&rsquo; or &lsquo;the other side&rsquo;) is the ancestor from whom the Hebrews take their name (Gen 10:24-25; 11:14-17). A Benjaminite bearing the name of the proto-ancestor of all Israelites collapses the genealogical distance between clan register and ethnic origin. Christ is &lsquo;the son of Abraham&rsquo; (Matt 1:1) — the fulfillment of the promise given to the Eber-Abraham-Isaac-Jacob-David line that these genealogies trace.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Abdon, Zichri, and Hanan — sons of Shashak. Hanan (<em>ḥānān</em>, &lsquo;gracious&rsquo;) shares the same root as Hannah, John, and Johanan — eight men named Hanan appear in Chronicles and Ezra-Nehemiah, reflecting the name&rsquo;s popularity as a covenant-grace marker. The grace embedded in these Benjaminite names anticipates the decisive arrival of grace in Christ: &lsquo;For from his fullness we have all received, grace upon grace. For the law was given through Moses; grace and truth came through Jesus Christ&rsquo; (John 1:16-17).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Hananiah, Elam, and Antothijah — sons of Shashak. Antothijah links this Benjaminite clan to Anathoth, Jeremiah&rsquo;s hometown (Jer 1:1). Jeremiah was the prophet of the new covenant (&lsquo;I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel,&rsquo; Jer 31:31-34, quoted at length in Heb 8:8-12 as fulfilled in Christ). A Benjaminite clan name derived from Anathoth ties this tribal register to the greatest prophetic announcement of the covenant that Christ establishes in his blood.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Iphedeiah and Penuel — sons of Shashak. Penuel (<em>pᵉnûʾēl</em>, &lsquo;face of God&rsquo;) is the place where Jacob wrestled with God and was renamed Israel (Gen 32:30). The name within Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy carries the full weight of that encounter. The NT presents the ultimate &lsquo;face of God&rsquo; encounter in Christ: &lsquo;For God, who said, &ldquo;Let light shine out of darkness,&rdquo; has shone in our hearts to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ&rsquo; (2 Cor 4:6).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Shamsherai, Shehariah, and Athaliah — sons of Jeroham. Athaliah (<em>ʿᵃṯalyāhû</em>, &lsquo;YHWH is exalted&rsquo;) is also the name of the queen-usurper who seized the Davidic throne and tried to kill all the royal seed (2 Chr 22:10-12) — the only woman to have occupied Judah&rsquo;s throne. Her attempt to exterminate the Davidic line failed because Jehosheba hid the infant Joash (2 Chr 22:11). The line that would produce Christ could not be exterminated by the most determined human effort — a pattern the NT affirms: &lsquo;the gates of Hades will not prevail against&rsquo; the community Christ builds (Matt 16:18).</p>",
    "27": "<p>Jaareshiah, Elijah, and Zichri — sons of Jeroham. Elijah (<em>ʾēlîyāhû</em>, &lsquo;my God is YHWH&rsquo;) is the prophet whose return was awaited as the forerunner of the Messiah (Mal 4:5), identified by Jesus as fulfilled in John the Baptist (Matt 11:14; 17:12-13). The name Elijah in Benjamin&rsquo;s genealogy is not predictive, but its pervasive use across Israel&rsquo;s registers reflects the Elijah tradition&rsquo;s hold on the messianic hope of the covenant community — the expectation of the forerunner who would prepare the way of the Lord.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&lsquo;These were heads of ancestral houses throughout their generations — leading men who lived in Jerusalem.&rsquo; The accumulation of Benjaminite families in Jerusalem reflects the deep roots of Benjamin&rsquo;s connection to the capital. Paul&rsquo;s identity as a Benjaminite (Phil 3:5) who carried the gospel from Jerusalem to Rome traces the arc from this Benjaminite residence in Jerusalem to the apostolic commission that Jerusalem-based disciples would execute in Christ&rsquo;s name across the Roman world (Acts 1:8: &lsquo;you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth&rsquo;).</p>",
    "29": "<p>The father of Gibeon — Gibeon was a major Benjaminite city that became the location of the bronze altar and tabernacle in David&rsquo;s day (1 Chr 21:29; 2 Chr 1:3) and the site where Solomon received wisdom in a dream (1 Kgs 3:4-5: YHWH appeared at &lsquo;the most important high place&rsquo; and offered Solomon anything he wished). The city where God offered and gave divine wisdom is rooted in Benjamin&rsquo;s tribal register — a foreshadowing of the one in whom &lsquo;are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&rsquo; (Col 2:3), the Christ who is &lsquo;the wisdom of God&rsquo; (1 Cor 1:24).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Abdon the firstborn, Zur, Kish, Baal, and Nadab — the sons of the father of Gibeon. Kish here will become Saul&rsquo;s father (v33). The name Baal within the Saulide genealogy reflects the religious syncretism the prophets condemned — and the NT fulfills Hosea&rsquo;s promise that the day will come when Israel calls YHWH &lsquo;my husband&rsquo; rather than &lsquo;my Baal&rsquo; (Hos 2:16-17). Christ is the husband of the new covenant community, replacing the Baal-worship with the exclusive covenant loyalty that the law demanded but could not produce.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gedor, Ahio, and Zacher — more sons of the Gibeonite ancestor. The household of Gibeon — Hivites who had obtained a treaty with Israel through deception (Josh 9) but were absorbed into Israel as servants of the sanctuary — is now recorded as progenitors of Saul&rsquo;s lineage. The Gibeonite inclusion within Israel (Josh 9:27: &lsquo;woodcutters and water-carriers for the congregation&rsquo;) is an OT type of the Gentile-inclusion into the covenant community, which Christ&rsquo;s mission enacts at a cosmic scale.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Mikloth fathered Shimeah. They lived in Jerusalem, opposite their kinsmen. The geographic note places real families in a real city, grounding the genealogy in lived geography. The NT&rsquo;s house-church communities in Rome (Rom 16) display the same pattern: small family groups across a major city constituting the body of Christ. In both cases, the community&rsquo;s identity is not a metaphysical abstraction but a social reality — families, households, neighbors — in which the covenant life is lived.</p>",
    "33": "<p>A shadow: &lsquo;Ner fathered Kish, Kish fathered Saul, and Saul fathered Jonathan, Malchishua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal.&rsquo; The Saulide genealogy carries immense Christological weight as the negative type that makes the positive type (David → Christ) legible. Saul was the king Israel demanded (&lsquo;give us a king like all the nations,&rsquo; 1 Sam 8:5) — chosen for human-standard qualifications (tall, handsome, militarily imposing). His rejection by YHWH demonstrates that no king chosen by human standards can fulfill the covenant. The contrast between Saul (the law-king, who ultimately brought death) and David (the grace-king, the man after YHWH&rsquo;s own heart) is the typological contrast Paul unpacks in Rom 5:12-21 between Adam and Christ: the first man brought death; the last man brought life.</p>",
    "34": "<p>A type: Jonathan&rsquo;s son was Meribbaal, and Meribbaal fathered Micah. Meribbaal (2 Sam 9: Mephibosheth) was Jonathan&rsquo;s son, lame from age five, who was brought to David&rsquo;s table to eat &lsquo;like one of the king&rsquo;s sons&rsquo; as an act of covenant-loyalty (<em>ḥesed</em>) to Jonathan. This is one of the richest types of grace in the OT: the lame man from the enemy-family, brought to the king&rsquo;s table and given a permanent place — not for his own merit but for the sake of a covenant his father had made. The type of the messianic feast is explicit in Luke 14:21: &lsquo;bring in the poor and crippled and blind and lame.&rsquo; Every gospel invitation to the sinner who has nothing to commend them is Meribbaal carried to David&rsquo;s table; Christ is the king whose covenant with the Father provides the ground for the invitation.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The sons of Micah — Pithon, Melech, Tarea, and Ahaz. The Saulide line continues beyond Meribbaal into further generations. The persistence of the Saulide genealogy even though the dynasty ended serves the Chronicler&rsquo;s purpose: no Israelite tribe or family is excluded from the covenant register, even those whose royal line failed. The gospel extends the same principle: no human failure disqualifies a person from the covenant invitation, because Christ&rsquo;s merit stands in place of every failed record (2 Cor 5:21: &lsquo;he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&rsquo;).</p>",
    "36": "<p>Ahaz fathered Jehoadah who fathered Alemeth, Azmaveth, and Zimri — the Saulide line branching generations below Meribbaal. The lineage&rsquo;s continuation demonstrates that YHWH&rsquo;s purposes for Benjamin do not depend on the dynasty maintaining political power. The covenant God who maintains the Saulide lineage through the collapse of their kingship is the same God who &lsquo;is able to do far more abundantly than all that we ask or think&rsquo; (Eph 3:20) — his faithfulness exceeds all dynastic failure.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Moza fathered Binea; Rapha, Eleasah, Azel — the Saulide line entering post-monarchic generations. By the Chronicler&rsquo;s era, this line has continued for perhaps fifteen or more generations after Saul&rsquo;s death. The survival of the Saulide genealogy demonstrates YHWH&rsquo;s covenant faithfulness to all twelve tribes, not only to the Davidic line. The Messiah comes from Judah (Gen 49:10; Mic 5:2) but the covenant people from whom he comes include Benjamin&rsquo;s preserved lineages — the twelve-tribe people are the soil from which the one Redeemer grows.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Azel had six sons — Azrikam, Bocheru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan. The name Ishmael within Benjamin&rsquo;s line (a covenant-child tribe bearing the name of the son excluded from the primary covenant line) demonstrates the permeability of Hebrew naming across ethnic memory. Paul&rsquo;s allegory in Gal 4:21-31 uses Ishmael and Isaac to represent law versus grace — and both names existed within Israel&rsquo;s genealogical registers, testimony to a community that held its full ancestral memory while living under the covenant of the Spirit.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The sons of Eshek, Azel&rsquo;s brother — Ulam the firstborn, Jeush the second, Eliphelet the third. Eliphelet (<em>ʾĕlîpeleṭ</em>, &lsquo;God is deliverance&rsquo;) was also the name of two of David&rsquo;s sons (1 Chr 3:6,8). The shared name across the Saulide and Davidic lines reflects the covenant community&rsquo;s shared naming vocabulary. Both the rejected dynasty and the chosen dynasty name their sons &lsquo;God is deliverance&rsquo; — the declaration is prophetic: the deliverance YHWH promised belongs not to one dynasty but to the covenant purpose that transcends dynasties and is fulfilled in Christ.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The chapter closes with Ulam&rsquo;s sons: mighty warriors, skilled archers, many sons and grandsons — one hundred and fifty in all. The chapter ends not with the Davidic line but with the Saulide line producing warriors and multiplying into a hundred and fifty covenant men. The closing image — the sons of the failed dynasty flourishing as skilled fighters — is a quiet statement about God&rsquo;s covenant faithfulness: even those whose ancestors failed the kingship test are preserved, enrolled, and numbered in the covenant community. That faithfulness is concentrated and fulfilled in Christ, the Son of David and Son of God, who does not fail where every previous anointed king failed — who is the &lsquo;better David&rsquo; whose kingdom is established forever (2 Sam 7:13; Heb 1:8: &lsquo;Your throne, O God, is forever and ever&rsquo;).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles', existing)
    v7 = len(CHRIST.get('7', {}))
    v8 = len(CHRIST.get('8', {}))
    print(f'1Chronicles 7-8 mkt-christ written ({v7} + {v8} = {v7+v8} verses).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
